###########################################################################################
#
# regression on all seven explanatory variable
# lm() is used to fit linear models, used to carry out regression.
#
# Summary gives information about 
# Residual standard error, which if close to 0, means it is good.
#
# Multiple R-squared is used for evaluating how well your model fits the data. They tell you 
# how much of the variance in the dependent variable (the predicted variable)  can be 
# explained by the independent variables (the predictor variables). 
# It also does not show if a regression model is satisfactory; it can show  an 
# R-squared figure for a good model, or a high R-squared figure for a model that doesn't fit.
#
#
# Adjusted R-squared gives the percentage of variation explained by only those independent
# variables that in reality affect the dependent variable. 
#
# F-statistic, p-value
# 
############################################################################################
m1=lm(GPM~.,data=FuelEff)

summary(m1)

##############################################################################################
# Here we are calculating all possible regressions and their R-squares, adjusted R-squares,
# and Cp-values. These calculation can be carried out using the function regsubsets() in the 
# R-package leaps.
###############################################################################################
# best subset regression in R
library(leaps)
X=FuelEff[,2:7] # design matrix or model formula for full model
y=FuelEff[,1]  # response vector

# nbest,number of subsets of each size to record
# nvmax,maximum size of subsets to examine
out=summary(regsubsets(X,y,nbest=2,nvmax=ncol(X)))
out

# The tab variable shows the trade-off between model size and model fit.
# The model with only one regressor,WT leads to an R-square of 85.8, which is very high, and

# Only this one variable explains most of the variability in fuel efficiency
# Adding displacement and number of cylinders to this model, increases the R-square to 90.3
# Cp value: Usually one should look for models where Cp value is small and close to the 
# number of predictors in the model plus the constant(p). Here 6.6 is a good Cp value.
#
##############################################################################################
tab=cbind(out$which,out$rsq,out$adjr2,out$cp)

#########################################################################################
#
# mean error->The mean error should be close to zero; a mean error different from zero
# indicates a bias in the forecasts.

# root mean square error ->The root mean square error expresses the forecast error in the
# units of the response variable.

# mean absolute percent error->The mean absolute percent forecast error expresses 
# the forecast error in percentage terms."
#
#########################################################################################

# Cross-validation for the regression on all six regressors
n<-length(FuelEff$GPM) 
diff<-perdiff<-obs<-pred<-dim(n)

for (i in 1:n){
  m1<-lm(GPM~.,data=FuelEff[-i,]) #training set,# remove observation i from dataset.
  pred=predict(m1,newdata=FuelEff[i,]) #validataion set
  obs=FuelEff$GPM[i] # real observation in this validation set
  diff[i]=obs-pred
  perdiff[i]<-abs(diff[i]/obs)
}
me=mean(diff) #mean error
me
## [1] -0.003981948
rmse=(mean(diff^2))^.5 #root mean square error
rmse
## [1] 0.3491357
mape=100*(mean(perdiff)) #mean absolute percent error
mape
## [1] 6.75226
# Cross-validation for the regression on weight only
for (k in 1:n) {
  m2=lm(GPM~WT,data=FuelEff[-k,])
  pred=predict(m2,newdat=FuelEff[k,])
  obs=FuelEff$GPM[k]
  diff[k]=obs-pred
  perdiff[k]=abs(diff[k])/obs
}

me1=mean(diff) # mean error
me1
## [1] -0.002960953
rmse1=(mean(diff^2))^.5 # root mean square error
rmse1
## [1] 0.4517422
mape1=100*(mean(perdiff)) # mean absolute percent error
mape1
## [1] 8.232507

#
# The objective here is to predict the sale price. 
# Scatter plots of price against age, mileage, and horsepower are shown as follows:
#
# There is curvature in the scatter plot of Price against Age. it is understandable that 
# as cars get old, its price goes down
# as number of killometers travelled by car increses, price gets down
# horsepower close to 120, price is highest.
#
#########################################################################################
plot(Price~Age,data=auto)

plot(Price~KM,data=auto)

plot(Price~HP,data=auto)

# regression on all data. R square and adjusted R square values are good. It explains 86.9%
# of the variation in price. F-statistic test for a significant linear regression relationship
# between the response variable and the predictor variable.
m1=lm(Price~.,data=auto)
summary(m1)

## density histograms and smoothed density histograms against time of eruption
hist(OldFaithful$TimeEruption,freq=FALSE)

## density histograms and smoothed density histograms against waiting time to next eruption
hist(OldFaithful$TimeWaiting,freq=FALSE)

fit2 <- locfit(~lp(TimeWaiting),data=OldFaithful)
plot(fit2)

#cross-validation of smoothing constant
# for waiting time to next eruption

#seq function used to generate regular sequences. Here starting from 0.20 to 1, interval = .01
alpha<-seq(0.20,1,by=0.01)
# calculating length of variable alpha
n1=length(alpha)
# Matrix function is used to create a matrix from the given set of values
g=matrix(nrow=n1,ncol=4)
# filling the matrix g with values using gcv function.
for (k in 1:length(alpha)) {
  g[k,]<-gcv(~lp(TimeWaiting,nn=alpha[k]),data=OldFaithful)
}
